{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1803"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1803"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.51,0.22,0.22,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"324"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"6475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise fit and healthy 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with pain in his scrotum. This has been ongoing since a groin injury during a soccer match two days ago. The pain has not abated with regular analgesia and ice packs applied to the groin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the right testis appears normal in position and size, with no abnormalities being found in this side of the scrotum. The left testis is in its correct position, is swollen, tender on palpation, and there is a palpably thickened cord. There is no overlying erythema of the skin. The testis does not transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrocele","Haematoma","Testicular torsion","Epididymitis","Testicular cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s acute pain in the scrotum is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaematoma\u003C/strong\u003E affecting the testis, particularly if the patient had a direct blow to his scrotum. The other condition to be considered and excluded is torsion of the testis. In a small proportion of cases, torsion can be precipitated by sport or injury, but this is very uncommon. Patients with torsion usually have pain of such severity that they seek prompt medical help, rather than waiting for two days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe underlying problem is unlikely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E as the testis does not transilluminate. The patient could have a secondary (traumatic) hydrocele following the trauma, which would not transilluminate, but would not explain the ongoing pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the relatively long time between the onset of symptoms and the patient\u0027s presentation, the absence of signs including absence of cremasteric reflex or high riding testicle makes \u003Cstrong\u003Etorsion\u003C/strong\u003E an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely cause of this patient\u0027s pain as this condition usually presents with gradual onset of scrotal pain, dysuria, frequency, or discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular cancer\u003C/strong\u003E tends to present as a painless scrotal swelling, but one of the modes of presentation is when the swelling first comes to the patient\u0027s notice after an injury or blow to the scrotum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute scrotal pain in a young man must always raise the possibility of testicular torsion.","Testicular haematoma can occur following trauma and presents with acute scrotal pain and swelling.","Testicular torsion typically presents with sudden onset severe pain and requires urgent surgical intervention."],"references":["Bourke MM, Silverberg JZ. Acute Scrotal Emergencies. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2019 Nov;37(4):593-610. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2019.07.002. Epub 2019 Aug 24. PMID: 31563197. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31563197/","Velasquez J, Boniface MP, Mohseni M. Acute Scrotum Pain. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470335/","Burnand K, Viswanath S, Kumar V, Chitale S. Acute spontaneous scrotal haematoma presenting with haemorrhagic shock: a case report. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2012 Jan;94(1):e1-2. doi: 10.1308/003588412x13171221498785. PMID: 22524901; PMCID: PMC3954209. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3954209/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:03:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:05:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1803"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19